<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is EPA-608 certification?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "EPA-608 is a federal certification program administered by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency under Section 608 of the Clean Air Act. Any technician who works with refrigerants — opening, maintaining, or repairing refrigerant-containing appliances — is required by federal law to hold this certification. There are four certification levels: Type I (small appliances under 5 pounds of refrigerant), Type II (high-pressure systems), Type III (low-pressure systems), and Universal (all types). Our technicians hold Universal certification, which covers every refrigerant-based appliance."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which appliances contain refrigerant?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Any appliance with a sealed cooling system contains refrigerant. This includes household refrigerators, freezers, wine coolers, wine cellars, under-counter refrigerators, all air conditioners and mini-splits, heat pumps, dehumidifiers, and all commercial refrigeration equipment. Built-in luxury refrigerators like Sub-Zero, Viking, and Thermador also fall under EPA-608 jurisdiction."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why is refrigerant dangerous to handle without certification?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Refrigerants are hazardous in several ways. Modern refrigerants like R-410A operate at significantly higher pressures than older refrigerants — an improperly opened line can release high-pressure gas that causes frostbite on contact with skin. Some refrigerants are flammable. Inhaling refrigerant vapors in concentrated form can cause cardiac arrest. And refrigerants are potent greenhouse gases — R-410A has a global warming potential nearly 2,000 times that of CO2, which is why the EPA mandates certified recovery before any refrigerant can be released."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does EPA-608 Universal certification mean?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Universal certification is the highest level — it covers all four certification types. A technician with Universal certification is qualified to work on small household appliances, residential refrigerators and freezers, air conditioning systems, heat pumps, and commercial refrigeration. Our technicians hold Universal certification, not limited Type I or II certifications."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if a technician releases refrigerant without certification?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Intentional venting of refrigerant is a federal violation under the Clean Air Act, subject to fines up to $44,539 per day per violation. Any technician opening a refrigerant circuit is legally required to recover the refrigerant using EPA-approved recovery equipment before making repairs and to be certified to handle the process. Uncertified technicians who work on refrigerant systems are violating federal law regardless of whether they vent or not."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need an EPA-608 certified technician for a refrigerator that isn't cooling?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Not necessarily — many refrigerator problems (thermostat failures, defrost heater issues, dirty condenser coils, door seal failures) don't require opening the sealed refrigerant system at all. But if the diagnosis reveals a refrigerant leak, a failed compressor, or a compromised sealed system, then yes — federal law requires a certified technician to handle the refrigerant. Our technicians are prepared for both scenarios on every service call."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who must certify recovery equipment for small appliances?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under EPA regulations, recovery equipment used for small appliances (those with under 5 pounds of refrigerant, such as household refrigerators and window AC units) must be tested and certified by an EPA-approved laboratory. This is a Type I requirement. The standard reference is the EPA Section 608 regulations under 40 CFR Part 82, Subpart F. The certifying body is an EPA-approved test laboratory, not ASHRAE or AHRI standards bodies directly — though AHRI 740 performance standards may be referenced by those labs."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

